My first car was a little white Toyota Camry.

Well, it was more two-toned: white with rust spots. It sported one lone hubcap and the back door on the passenger side refused to open. On the inside, the tint was peeling off the windows and the upholstery on the ceiling was falling down. Once, in the middle of Texas, my automatic seat belts refused to strap me in, so I had to disconnect the wire and rewind them by hand.

I shivered under my coat during the winter and melted during the summer. (I took many nighttime road trips during the summer.)

One time, after pulling me over in my little hometown, a cop called in two backups. I can’t imagine what judgments he made about me. As he walked up to my window, he looked at my car and asked, "Do you know your car is making a funny noise?

Yes. Yes, I did.

But I didn't care. I didn't care what kind of car I drove, and I didn't care to spend any time or money fixing all its little problems. My friends probably thought I was crazy, but if I didn't mind, why should I care what my friends thought?

**I didn't realize then but my rusty Camry was a parable of my life.**

**The Broken Engine Inside Me**

I lived life with battered, rusted-out mindsets and habits. I’d glimpse success but never quite reach it. All of the broken parts seemed normal, so I never noticed them, much less took the time to fix them.

That is when I entered the most difficult season of my life. It forced me to slow down, stop focusing on what was happening around me and start focusing on what was happening within me.

To keep from getting stranded or lost along the way, you should do three things:

First, take a look under the hood, dig into the engine and give it the tune-up or overhaul it needs. Next, plan your trip and get familiar with your destination. Once you’ve done this, you can put the petal to the metal and hit the road\!

**Overhaul Your Engine**

Under the hood of your car is an engine. It provides the power to propel your car forward. The external beauty of your car doesn’t really matter because it's the engine that determines how fast and far you can go. Any aerodynamic additions or hot features are mere tweaks.

Right now, your life is being propelled by an engine, consisting of your thoughts, beliefs, and unique perspective of the world. 

This is where success begins: on the inside. If you want to go further and faster, you don't need to stomp the gas harder. 

You need to overhaul your engine so it runs more effectively and smoothly.

**Develop Your GPS**

During one of my many night-time road trips, I was excitedly talking on the phone (probably to keep myself awake). I became so distracted, I missed the only important turnoff of the entire trip. Thirty minutes blew by before I realized I was speeding away from my destination.

This time, the fault wasn't the engine but my direction.

Develop your personal GPS: know clearly the things most important to you--that is, where you want to go. Once you  know your destination and the course to get there, all you need to do is make sure you stay on course.

Transition becomes difficult when we don't have fixed reference points--things we can use to reorient ourselves in new situations. So develop your GPS and follow it.

By shifting your life into a higher gear, you can accomplish more things with less effort.

Operating at your highest level gives you the power to pursue your dreams and start executing.

Why road-trip half-heartedly? Take a little time to fix your engine, learn your destination, and manage your fuel.
